You got it! Here's a simple HTML, CSS, and JavaScript script to create a form that collects user text input and displays it back to them. This is a great example to illustrate how user input is handled in web development.

**HTML (index.html):**

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
<title>Simple Text Input Form</title>
<style>
  body {
    font-family: sans-serif;
  }
  label {
    display: block;
    margin-bottom: 5px;
  }
  input[type="text"] {
    width: 200px;
    padding: 8px;
    margin-bottom: 10px;
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
  }
  button {
    padding: 8px 15px;
    background-color: #4CAF50;
    color: white;
    border: none;
    cursor: pointer;
  }
</style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Enter Your Name</h1>

  <form id="myForm">
    <label for="name">Your Name:</label>
    <input type="text" id="name" name="name">

    <button type="button" onclick="displayMessage()">Submit</button>
  </form>

  <p id="message"></p>

  <script src="script.js"></script> </body>
</html>
```

**JavaScript (script.js):**

```javascript
function displayMessage() {
  const nameInput = document.getElementById("name");
  const messageElement = document.getElementById("message");

  const enteredName = nameInput.value;
  messageElement.textContent = "Hello, " + enteredName + "!";
}
```

**Explanation:**

1. **HTML:**
   - Sets up a basic form with a text input field (`<input type="text">`) and a button.
   - Includes basic CSS styling for the form elements.
   - Links to the `script.js` file for JavaScript functionality.

2. **JavaScript:**
   - The `displayMessage()` function is called when the button is clicked.
   - It retrieves the value entered in the text input field using `document.getElementById("name").value`.
   - It then updates the content of the `<p>` element with an appropriate greeting using `document.getElementById("message").textContent`.

**Workshop Steps:**

1. **Show the Code:** Display the HTML and JavaScript code on the screen.
2. **Explain the Structure:** Walk through the HTML code, explaining the purpose of each element (form, input field, button, etc.).
3. **Highlight the JavaScript:** Focus on the `displayMessage()` function and explain how it handles user input.
4. **Live Demonstration:** Open the HTML file in a browser and demonstrate how the form works.
5. **Interactive Exercise:** Encourage participants to modify the code (e.g., change the greeting message, add more input fields) and see the results in real-time.



